 mit Stermann & Grissemann |publisher=wien ORF.at |date=2012-05-01 |accessdate=2012-09-29}}</ref>\n*{{Esc|Belgium}} \u2013 ''Dutch:'' [[Andr\u00e9 Vermeulen]] and Anja Daems ([[\u00e9\u00e9n|VRT TV1]]), Julien Put and [[Michel Follet]] ([[Radio 2 (Belgium)|VRT Radio 2]]),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vrtfansite.be/nieuws_template.php?id=9753 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120303110540/http://www.vrtfansite.be/nieuws_template.php?id=9753 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2012-03-03 |title=Congratulations: 50 jaar Songfestival! |publisher=VRTFansite.be |accessdate=2012-08-09}}</ref><br>''French:'' [[Jean-Pierre Hautier]] ([[La Une|RTBF La Une]]), Laurent Daube and \u00c9ric Russon ([[La Premi\u00e8re|RTBF La Premi\u00e8re]])<ref name=\"songcontest.free.fr\"/>\n*{{Esc|Belarus}} \u2013 Alex Krugliyakov ([[Belarus-1|BT]])\n*{{Esc|Cyprus|1960}} \u2013 Evi Papamichail ([[Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation|RIK 1]])<ref>Savvidis, Christos (OGAE Cyprus)</ref>\n*{{Esc|Finland}} \u2013 [[Jani Juntunen]] and Asko Murtom\u00e4ki ([[YLE TV1]]),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.viisukuppila.fi/phpBB3/yleista/topic1578.html?sid=4004772ec986da0c3795a6f5dd54f0d4 |title=Selostajat ja taustalaulajat l\u0102\u00a4pi vuosien? \u2022 Viisukuppila |publisher=Viisukuppila.fi |date= |accessdate=2012-08-09}}</ref> Iris Mattilal\u00e4hde and Tarja N\u00e4rhi ([[YLE Radio Suomi]])\n*{{Esc|Macedonia}} \u2013 Milanka Ra\u0161ik ([[MTV 2 (Macedonia)|MTV 2]])\n*{{Esc|Romania}} \u2013 [[Andreea Marin]] & [[Leonard Miron]] ([[TVR2]])\n*{{Esc|Switzerland}} \u2013 ''German:'' [[Sandra Studer]] ([[SF zwei|SF2]]), ''French:'' Phil Mundwiller ([[TSR 1]]), ''Italian:'' Jonathan Tedesco ([[RSI La 1|TSI 1]])\n*{{Esc|FR Yugoslavia}}{{ref|b|2}} \u2013 ''Unknown'' (Yu Info)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rtvforum.net/thread-1160-post-143643.html#pid143643 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150929115410/http://www.rtvforum.net/thread-1160-post-143643.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=2015-09-29 |title=Nostalgi\u010dni RTV press clipping |publisher=rtvforum.net |accessdate=2015-09-02}}</ref>\n{{Div col end}}\n\n: 1.{{note|a}} Although Australia was not eligible to enter the contest at the time, the event was broadcast on [[Special Broadcasting Service|SBS]]. As is the case each year, it did not however broadcast it live due to the difference in Australian time zones. This year, the broadcast contained a locally produced addition of a studio audience of young representatives from the competing countries. However, a number of complaints saw the United Kingdom's broadcast, including commentary from [[Terry Wogan]], shown a few weeks later.<ref>[http://www.sbs.com.au/annualreports/sbsannualreport2001.pdf] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070922084530/http://www.sbs.com.au/annualreports/sbsannualreport2001.pdf|date=22 September 2007}}</ref>\n\n: 2.{{note|b}} After the [[breakup of Yugoslavia]], the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia last participated in [[Eurovision Song Contest 1992|1992]]. ''YU Info channel'' broadcast the show, although Yugoslavia did not participate.\n\n==Official album==\n{{Infobox album\n| italic_title = no\n| name         = Eurovision Song Contest: Copenhagen 2001\n| type         = compilation\n| artist       = [[Eurovision Song Contest]]\n| cover        = ESC 2001 album cover.jpg\n| alt          =\n| released     = 5 May 2001\n| recorded     =\n| venue        =\n| studio       =\n| genre        = [[Pop music|Pop]]\n| length       = {{Duration|m=70|s=09}}\n| label        = [[EMI Records|EMI]] / [[CMC International|CMC]]\n| producer     =\n| prev_title   = [[Eurovision Song Contest 2000#Official album|Eurovision Song Contest: Stockholm 2000]]\n| prev_year    = 2000\n| next_title   = [[Eurovision Song Contest 2002#Official album|Eurovision Song Contest: Tallinn 2002]]\n| next_year    = 2002\n}}\n'''''Eurovision Song Contest: Copenhagen 2001''''' was the official compilation album of the 2001 Contest, put together by the European Broadcasting Union and released by [[EMI Records]] and [[CMC International]] on 5 May 2001. The album featured all 23 songs that entered in the 2001 contest.<ref>{{cite web|title=Eurovision Song Contest: Copenhagen 2001|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/release/eurovision-song-contest-copenhagen-2001-mr0002802506/credits|website=allmusic.com|publisher=Allmusic|accessdate=5 November 2014}}</ref>\n{{tracklist\n| headline        = Track listing\n| extra_column    = Artist\n| total_length    = {{Duration|m=70|s=09}}\n| note1 = {{Esccnty|Netherlands}}\n| extra1 = [[Michelle Courtens]]\n| title1 = [[Out on My Own (Michelle song)|Out on My Own]]\n| length1 = 3:21\n| note2 = {{Esccnty|Iceland}}\n| extra2 = [[Two Tricky]]\n| title2 = [[Angel (Two Tricky song)|Angel]]\n| length2 = 3:06\n| note3 = {{Esccnty|Bosnia and Herzegovina}}\n| extra3 = [[Nino Pr\u0161e\u0161]]\n| title3 = [[Hano (song)|Hano]]\n| length3 = 3:00\n| note4 = {{Esccnty|Norway}}\n| extra4 = [[Haldor L\u00e6greid]]\n| title4 = [[On My Own (Haldor L\u00e6greid song)|On My Own]]\n| length4 = 3:04\n| note5 = {{Esccnty|Israel}}\n| extra5 =[[Tal Sondak]]\n| title5 = [[En Davar]]\n| length5 = 3:03\n| note6 =  {{Esccnty|Russia}}\n| extra6 = [[Mumiy Troll]]\n| title6 = [[Lady Alpine Blue]]\n| length6 = 3:00\n| note7 = {{Esccnty|Sweden}}\n| extra7 = [[Friends (group)|Friends]]\n| title7 = [[Listen To Your Heartbeat]]\n| length7 = 3:04\n| note8 = {{Esccnty|Lithuania}}\n| extra8 = [[SKAMP]]\n| title8 = [[You Got Style]]\n| length8 = 2:58\n| note9 = {{Esccnty|Latvia}}\n| extra9 = [[Arnis Mednis]]\n| title9 = [[Too Much (Arnis Mednis song)|Too Much]]\n| length9 = 2:52\n| note10 = {{Esccnty|Croatia}}\n| extra10 =[[Vanna (singer)|Vanna]] \n| title10 =[[Strings of My Heart]]\n| length10 = 2:58\n| note11 = {{Esccnty|Portugal}}\n| extra11 = [[MTM (group)|MTM]]\n| title11 = [[S\u00f3 sei ser feliz assim]]\n| length11 = 3:02\n| note12 = {{Esccnty|Ireland}}\n| extra12 = [[Gary O'Shaughnessy]]\n| title12 = [[Without Your Love (Gary O'Shaughnessy song)|Without Your Love]]\n| length12 = 3:00\n| note13 = {{Esccnty|Spain}}\n| extra13 = [[David Civera]]\n| title13 = [[Dile que la quiero]]\n| length13 = 2:56\n| note14 = {{Esccnty|France}}\n| extra14 = [[Natasha St-Pier]]\n| title14 = [[Je n'ai que mon \u00e2me]]\n| length14 = 2:50\n| note15 = {{Esccnty|Turkey}}\n| extra15 = [[Turkey in the Eurovision Song Contest|Sedat Y\u00fcce]]\n| title15 = [[Sevgiliye Son]]\n| length15 = 3:00\n| note16 = {{Esccnty|United Kingdom}}\n| extra16 = [[Lindsay Dracass]]\n| title16 = [[No Dream Impossible]]\n| length16 = 3:02\n| note17 = {{Esccnty|Slovenia}}\n| extra17 = [[Nu\u0161a Derenda]]\n| title17 = [[Energy (Nu\u0161a Derenda song)|Energy]]\n| length17 = 2:58\n| note18 = {{Esccnty|Poland}}\n| extra18 = [[Andrzej Piaseczny|Piasek]]\n| title18 = [[2 Long]]\n| length18 = 3:03\n| note19 = {{Esccnty|Germany}}\n| extra19 = [[Michelle (German singer)|Michelle]]\n| title19 = [[Wer Liebe lebt|To Live For Love]]\n| length19 = 4:06\n| note20 = {{Esccnty|Estonia}}\n| extra20 = [[Tanel Padar]], [[Dave Benton]], [[Soul Militia|2XL]]\n| title20 = [[Everybody (Tanel Padar and Dave Benton song)|Everybody]]\n| length20 = 2:56\n| note21 = {{Esccnty|Malta}}\n| extra21 = [[Fabrizio Faniello]]\n| title21 = [[Another Summer Night]]\n| length21 = 2:54\n| note22 = {{Esccnty|Greece}}\n| extra22 = [[Antique (duo)|Antique]]\n| title22 = [[Die for You (Antique song)|Die for You]]\n| length22 = 2:56\n| note23 = {{Esccnty|Denmark}}\n| extra23 = [[Rollo & King]] \n| title23 = [[Never Ever Let You Go]]\n| length23 = 3:00\n}}\n\n=== Charts ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2001)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br /> position\n|-\n{{albumchart|GermanyComp|4|M|title=Eurovision Song Contest 2001|url=https://www.offiziellecharts.de/compilation-details-14495|work=Offiziellecharts.de|publisher=[[GfK Entertainment Charts]]|rowheader=true|accessdate=17 March 2018}}\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Official website|http://www.eurovision.tv/}}\n\n{{Eurovision years}}\n{{Eurovision Song Contest 2001}}\n{{Eurovision Song Contest's Greatest Hits}}\n{{Aqua (band)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2012}}\n{{coord|55|42|08.89|N|12|34|19.93|E|type:landmark_region:DK_scale:2000|display=title}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Eurovision Song Contest by year]]\n[[Category:2001 music festivals]]\n[[Category:2001 in Denmark]]\n[[Category:Eurovision Song Contest 2001| ]]\n[[Category:2000s in Copenhagen]]\n[[Category:Culture in Copenhagen]]\n[[Category:May 2001 events in Europe]]\n[[Category:Events in Copenhagen]]\n", "text_old": "{{active editnotice}} <!-- See [[Wikipedia:Editnotice]] -->\n{{Infobox Song Contest\n| name = Eurovision Song Contest\n| year = 2001\n| logo = ESC 2001 logo.svg\n| final = {{start date|2001|05|12|df=y}}\n| venue = [[Parken Stadium]]<br>Copenhagen, Denmark\n| presenters = {{unbulleted list|[[Natasja Crone Back]]|[[S\u00f8ren Pilmark]]}}\n| director = Jan Frifelt\n| exsupervisor = Christine Marchal-Ortiz\n| exproducer = J\u00f8rgen Ramskov\n| host = [[Danmarks Radio]] (DR)\n| opening = \"[[Fly on the Wings of Love]]\" and \"Walk Right Back\" performed by the [[Olsen Brothers]]\n| interval = Medley of [[Aqua (band)|Aqua]] hits performed by [[Aqua (band)|Aqua]] feat. [[Safri Duo]]\n| entries = 23\n| debut = None\n| return = {{unbulleted list|{{Esc|Bosnia and Herzegovina}}|{{Esc|Greece}}|{{Esc|Lithuania|1988}}|{{Esc|Poland}}|{{Esc|Portugal}}|{{Esc|Slovenia}}}}\n| nonreturn = {{unbulleted list|{{Esc|Austria}}|{{Esc|Belgium}}|{{Esc|Cyprus|1960}}|{{Esc|Finland}}|{{Esc|Macedonia}}|{{Esc|Romania}}|{{Esc|Switzerland}}}}\n| Green = Y \n| Green SA = \n| Purple = \n| Red = \n| Yellow = Y\n| vote = Each country awarded 12, 10, 8-1 points to their 10 favourite songs.\n| null = None\n| winner = {{unbulleted list|{{esc|Estonia|y=2001}}|\"[[Everybody (Tanel Padar and Dave Benton song)|Everybody]]\"}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Eurovision Song Contest 2001''' was the 46th edition of the annual [[Eurovision Song Contest]]. It took place in [[Copenhagen]], [[Denmark]], following the [[Olsen Brothers]]' win at the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2000|2000 contest]] in [[Stockholm]], [[Sweden]] with the song \"[[Fly on the Wings of Love]]\".\nThe hosting marked the second time the contest was held on Danish soil, after the [[Eurovision Song Contest 1964|1964 contest]] - 37 years earlier.\n23 countries took part in the contest, which was held on 12 May 2001. The host venue was the [[Parken Stadium]] - the largest venue to ever host the contest as of 2019. A total of 35,000 spectators saw the show live from within the stadium, breaking the record of 16,000 held by the previous year's hosts [[Sweden]].<ref name=ESC2001/>\n\nThe show was opened by the Olsen Brothers, with a snippet from their winning song \"[[Fly on the Wings of Love]]\", followed by their latest single \"Walk Right Back\", which was already a smash hit in Denmark at the time. \nThe presenters were Danish journalist and TV-show presenter [[Natasja Crone Back]] and the famous Danish actor [[S\u00f8ren Pilmark]] who spoke most of their announcements in rhyming couplets.\n\n[[France]], [[Greece]] and [[Slovenia]] were the heavy favourites to win the contest; however, as the voting progressed it became a two-horse race between [[Estonia]] and the host country Denmark.<ref name=\"Decade\" />\nThe contest was won by [[Estonia in the Eurovision Song Contest|Estonia]], represented by [[Tanel Padar]], [[Dave Benton]] & [[Soul Militia|2XL]] with the song [[Everybody (Tanel Padar and Dave Benton song)|\"Everybody\"]], written by [[Ivar Must]] and Maian-Anna Karmas, which scored a total of 198 points. The host nation, Denmark, finished in 2nd place with 177 points. Coming 3rd were Greece with 147 points - giving the country their best result up until this point. France came 4th with 142 points, and in 5th place were Sweden with 100 points.\n\nDave Benton, who was born and raised in [[Aruba]], was the first [[black people|black person]] and, at the age of 50 years and 101 days, the oldest contestant at the time to win the contest.<ref name=ESC2001>{{cite web|title=Eurovision Song Contest 2001|url=http://www.eurovision.tv/page/history/by-year/contest?event=266 |publisher=[[EBU]]|accessdate=14 June 2012}}</ref> Furthermore, this was first victory for an [[Eastern Europe|Eastern European]] country, one of the [[Baltic states]] and one of the former [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] republic.\n\n== Location ==\n{{details|topic=the host city|Copenhagen}}\n[[File:Parken 02.JPG|thumb|left|220px|Parken Stadium, Copenhagen - host venue of the 2001 contest.]]\n\n[[Copenhagen]], the capital of [[Denmark]] was the host city for the 46th edition of Eurovision. The venue choice for the contest was [[Parken Stadium]], a [[football (soccer)|football]] [[stadium]] in the [[Indre \u00d8sterbro]] district of [[Copenhagen]], [[Denmark]], built from 1990\u20131992.\n\nThe [[Danmarks Radio|Danish national broadcaster]] (DR) faced some problems whilst organising the contest such as a lack of funds and the search for a suitable venue. The three largest cities in Denmark - [[Copenhagen]], [[Aarhus]] and [[Odense]] - all made bids to host the contest. Eventually, DR chose the large football stadium [[Parken]] as the host venue, after the company running the stadium agreed to add a retractable roof to the building. This solution made it the biggest venue ever to host a Eurovision Song Contest, but the scale of it wasn't entirely a success: many of the 38,000 people in the audience could not see the stage, and for many entries the hall appeared to be too big.<ref name=\"Decade\">{{cite web|url=http://www.eurovision.tv/page/news?id=7743&_t=The+end+of+a+decade%3A+Copenhagen+2001|title=The end of a decade: Copenhagen 2001|last=Bakker|first=Sietse|date=2009-12-22|publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]]|accessdate=22 December 2009}}</ref>\n\n{{location map+ |Denmark |relief=yes |float=left |width=220 |caption=Locations of the candidate cities: the chosen host city is marked in blue, while the eliminated cities are marked in red. |places=\n<small>{{location map~ |Denmark |lat=56.1572 |long=10.2107 |label=[[Aarhus]]|mark=Red pog.svg|marksize=7}}</small>\n{{location map~ |Denmark |lat=55.676111 |long=12.568333 |label=<u>'''[[Copenhagen]]'''</u>|mark=Blue pog.svg|marksize=7|position=bottom}}\n<small>{{location map~ |Denmark |lat=55.395833 |long=10.388611 |label=[[Odense]]|mark=Red pog.svg|marksize=7|position=bottom}}</small>\n}}\n\n=== Format ===\nThe logo of the 2001 Eurovision Song Contest was made out of four circles, placed in the shape of a heart. The four circles were also present in the stage design, with the light construction was made of the same four rings.<ref name=\"Decade\"/>\n\nChanges occurred in the qualification process for the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2002|2002 Contest]]: along with the \"Big 4\" countries, the top 15 placed countries would qualify for next year's competition. The other spots for 2002 would be filled by countries that were excluded from the 2001 contest because of their low point average for the years 1996\u20132000.<ref name=\"Decade\" />\n\n=== Incidents ===\nControversy was again rife in the contest: the [[United Kingdom]] TV commentator [[Terry Wogan]] repeatedly made critical comments about the hosts and dubbed them \"Doctor Death and the Tooth Fairy/The Little Mermaid\" after providing their entire commentary in rhyming couplets.<ref name=\"comments\">{{cite news |first=Geir |last=Evensen |title=Wogan i hardt v\u00e6r |url=http://www.nrk.no/programmer/tv/melodi_grand_prix/1.1259345 |work=NRK |date=16 May 2001 |accessdate=16 September 2014 |language=Norwegian}}</ref> The Danes were so offended that the [[British Broadcasting Corporation|BBC]] was obliged to issue an apology on Wogan's comments.<ref name=\"comments\"/> Controversy also surrounded the Swedish song, \"[[Listen To Your Heartbeat]]\", which was repeatedly accused as a plagiarism of the [[Belgium|Belgian]] entry for the [[Eurovision Song Contest 1996|1996 Contest]], \"[[Liefde is een kaartspel]]\".<ref>{{cite news |first=Jan |last=Eriksen |title=The Swedish song \u2013 a rip-off? |url=http://esc2001.dr.dk/doc_5826.html |work=Eurovision Song Contest 2001 official website |date=22 March 2000 |accessdate=16 September 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010312174351/http://esc2001.dr.dk/doc_5826.html |archivedate=12 March 2001}}</ref> Eventually the EBU decided for the matter to be settled in court, with the song allowed to compete as long as the courts did not declare the song as plagiarism.<ref name=\"Decade\" /><ref>{{cite news |title=Swedish song cleared for Copenhagen by EBU |url=http://www.eurosong.org.uk/news/stories/copyrow.htm |work=Eurovision Song Contest |accessdate=16 September 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010418055151/http://www.eurosong.org.uk/news/stories/copyrow.htm |archivedate=18 April 2001}}</ref>\nAt first this was denied by the Swedish songwriters, one of whom was [[Thomas G:son]], but after the Belgian songwriters and the author's organisation [[SABAM]] pressed for legal action, a cash settlement was agreed.<ref>[http://www.esctoday.com/1744/swedish_entry_2001_now_officially_plagiarism/ ESCtoday.com, ''Swedish entry 2001 now officially plagiarism'']</ref><ref>Leif Thorsson. ''Melodifestivalen genom tiderna'' [\"Melodifestivalen through time\"] (2006), p.&nbsp;290. Stockholm: Premium Publishing AB. {{ISBN|91-89136-29-2}}</ref>\n\nDuring the voting the Danish band [[Aqua (band)|Aqua]] performed with a medley of their singles, with percussion ensemble [[Safri Duo]] performing in the medley.<ref name=\"Decade\" /> Although enjoyable, people complained about it being a little bit \"rude\" as there was some swearing during the performance, both at the beginning and end of \"[[Barbie Girl]]\".\n\n== Participating countries ==\n{{Further|List of countries in the Eurovision Song Contest}}\nDue to the EBU's relegation rule of the lowest ranked countries from the contest had to miss the follow year's contest, meant several countries could not participate, while relegated countries from the [[ESC 1999|1999 contest]] were able to return this year.  [[Bosnia and Herzegovina in the Eurovision Song Contest|Bosnia and Herzegovina]], [[Greece in the Eurovision Song Contest|Greece]], [[Lithuania in the Eurovision Song Contest|Lithuania]], [[Poland in the Eurovision Song Contest|Poland]], [[Portugal in the Eurovision Song Contest|Portugal]], and [[Slovenia in the Eurovision Song Contest|Slovenia]] returned, while [[Austria in the Eurovision Song Contest|Austria]], [[Belgium in the Eurovision Song Contest|Belgium]], [[Cyprus in the Eurovision Song Contest|Cyprus]], [[Finland in the Eurovision Song Contest|Finland]], [[Macedonia in the Eurovision Song Contest|Macedonia]], [[Romania in the Eurovision Song Contest|Romania]], and [[Switzerland in the Eurovision Song Contest|Switzerland]], the seven countries with the lowest average result in the past five contests, were relegated.  This brought the total number of participating countries to twenty-three.<ref name=ESC2001/>\n\n=== Returning artists ===\n[[Tanel Padar]] was a backing vocalist for [[Eda-Ines Etti|Ines]] in [[Eurovision Song Contest 2000|2000]].\n\n==Results==\n''Countries in bold were allowed to compete in the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2002]].''\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#ccc;\"\n! Draw\n! Country\n! Artist\n! Song\n! Language<ref>{{cite web|title=Eurovision Song Contest 2001|url=http://www.diggiloo.net/?2001|publisher=The Diggiloo Thrush|accessdate=5 March 2012}}</ref>\n! Place\n! Points\n|-\n| 01\n| {{Esc|Netherlands|y=2001}}\n| [[Michelle Courtens|Michelle]]\n| \"[[Out on My Own (Michelle song)|Out on My Own]]\"\n| [[English language|English]]\n| 18\n| 16\n|- \n| 02\n| {{Esc|Iceland|y=2001}}\n| [[Two Tricky]]\n| \"[[Angel (Two Tricky song)|Angel]]\"\n| English\n| 22\n| 3\n|- \n| 03\n| '''{{Esc|Bosnia and Herzegovina|y=2001}}'''\n| [[Nino Pr\u0161e\u0161]]\n| \"[[Hano (song)|Hano]]\"\n| [[Bosnian language|Bosnian]], English\n| 14\n| 29\n|- \n| 04\n| {{Esc|Norway|y=2001}}\n| [[Haldor L\u00e6greid]]\n| \"[[On My Own (Haldor L\u00e6greid song)|On My Own]]\"\n| English\n| 22\n| 3\n|- \n| 05\n| '''{{Esc|Israel|y=2001}}'''\n| [[Tal Sondak]]\n| \"[[En Davar]]\" {{small|(\u05d0\u05d9\u05df \u05d3\u05d1\u05e8)}}\n| [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]]\n| 16\n| 25\n|-\n| 06\n| '''{{Esc|Russia|y=2001}}'''\n| [[Mumiy Troll]]\n| \"[[Lady Alpine Blue]]\"\n| English\n| 12\n| 37\n|-\n| 07\n| '''{{Esc|Sweden|y=2001}}'''\n| [[Friends (Swedish band)|Friends]]\n| \"[[Listen to Your Heartbeat]]\"\n| English\n| 5\n| 100\n|-  \n| 08\n| '''{{Esc|Lithuania|1988|y=2001}}'''\n| [[SKAMP]]\n| \"[[You Got Style]]\"\n| English, [[Lithuanian language|Lithuanian]]\n| 13\n| 35\n|- \n| 09\n| {{Esc|Latvia|y=2001}}{{ref|i|1}}\n| [[Arnis Mednis]]\n| \"[[Too Much (Arnis Mednis song)|Too Much]]\"\n| English\n| 18\n| 16\n|- \n| 10\n| '''{{Esc|Croatia|y=2001}}'''\n| [[Vanna (singer)|Vanna]]\n| \"[[Strings of My Heart]]\"\n| English\n| 10\n| 42\n|- \n| 11\n| '''{{Esc|Portugal|y=2001}}'''{{ref|i|1}}\n| [[MTM (band)|MTM]]\n| \"[[S\u00f3 sei ser feliz assim]]\"\n| [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]]\n| 17\n| 18\n|- \n| 12\n| {{Esc|Ireland|y=2001}}\n| [[Gary O'Shaughnessy]]\n| \"[[Without Your Love (Gary O'Shaughnessy song)|Without Your Love]]\"\n| English\n| 21\n| 6\n|-\n| 13\n| '''{{Esc|Spain|y=2001}}'''\n| [[David Civera]]\n| \"[[Dile que la quiero]]\"\n| [[Spanish language|Spanish]]\n| 6\n| 76\n|- \n| 14\n| '''{{Esc|France|y=2001}}'''\n| [[Natasha St-Pier]]\n| \"[[Je n'ai que mon \u00e2me]]\"\n| [[French language|French]], English\n| 4\n| 142\n|- \n| 15\n| '''{{Esc|Turkey|y=2001}}'''\n| [[Sedat Y\u00fcce]]\n| \"[[Sevgiliye Son]]\"\n| [[Turkish language|Turkish]], English\n| 11\n| 41\n|- \n| 16\n| '''{{Esc|United Kingdom|y=2001}}'''\n| [[Lindsay Dracass]]\n| \"[[No Dream Impossible]]\"\n| English\n| 15\n| 28\n|- \n| 17\n| '''{{Esc|Slovenia|y=2001}}'''\n| [[Nu\u0161a Derenda]]\n| \"[[Energy (Nu\u0161a Derenda song)|Energy]]\"\n| English\n| 7\n| 70\n|-\n| 18\n| {{Esc|Poland|y=2001}}\n| [[Andrzej Piaseczny|Piasek]]\n| \"[[2 Long (Andrzej Piaseczny song)|2 Long]]\"\n| English\n| 20\n| 11\n|- \n| 19\n| '''{{Esc|Germany|y=2001}}'''\n| [[Michelle (German singer)|Michelle]]\n| \"[[Wer Liebe lebt]]\"\n| [[German language|German]], English\n| 8\n| 66\n|- style=\"font-weight:bold; background: gold;\"\n| 20\n| '''{{Esc|Estonia|y=2001}}'''\n| [[Tanel Padar]], [[Dave Benton]] & [[Soul Militia|2XL]]\n| \"[[Everybody (Tanel Padar and Dave Benton song)|Everybody]]\"\n| English\n| 1\n| 198\n|- \n| 21\n| '''{{Esc|Malta|y=2001}}'''\n| [[Fabrizio Faniello]]\n| \"[[Another Summer Night]]\"\n| English\n| 9\n| 48\n|-\n| 22\n| '''{{Esc|Greece|y=2001}}'''\n| [[Antique (band)|Antique]]\n| \"[[(I Would) Die for You]]\"\n| [[Greek language|Greek]], English\n| 3\n| 147\n|-\n| 23\n| '''{{Esc|Denmark|y=2001}}'''\n| [[Rollo & King]]\n| \"[[Never Ever Let You Go]]\"\n| English\n| 2\n| 177\n|}\n: 1.{{note|i}}After Portugal did not enter in the 2002 contest, their place for the 2002 contest final was awarded to Latvia.\n\n== Scoreboard ==\nThe majority of participating countries held a televote, where the top ten most voted for songs were awarded the 12, 10, 8, 7, 6, 5, 4, 3, 2, 1 points. This year the EBU introduced for the first time a mix of voting systems (50% televoting and 50% jury) for those countries that didn't want to use 100% televoting. Only three votes were allowed per household.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.myledbury.co.uk/eurovision/pdf/esc2001.pdf |title= Rules of Eurovision Song Contest 2001|publisher=myledbury|date= |accessdate=9 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the EBU rules (published on 05/10/00), every broadcaster was free to make a choice between the full televoting system and the mixed 50-50 system. In exceptional circumstances, where televoting was not possible at all, only a jury was used: Bosnia and Herzegovina, Turkey and Russia. Only a few countries are confirmed to have used the mixed voting system: Croatia, Greece and Malta.\n \n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:85%;\"\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:left; background:#F2F2F2\"| Voting procedure used:<br />\n{{legend|#EFA4A9|100% Televoting|outline=#AAAAAA}}{{legend|#A4EAA9|50% Jury & televote|outline=#AAAAAA}}{{legend|#A4D1EF|100% Jury vote|outline=#AAAAAA}}</td>\n! colspan=\"25\" | Voters\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\" {{vert header|nb=1|Total score}}\n! {{vert header|nb=1|Netherlands}}\n! {{vert header|nb=1|Iceland}}\n! {{vert header|nb=1|Bosnia and Herzegovina}}\n! {{vert header|nb=1|Norway}}\n! {{vert header|nb=1|Israel}}\n! {{vert header|nb=1|Russia}}\n! {{vert header|nb=1|Sweden}}\n! {{vert header|nb=1|Lithuania}}\n! {{vert header|nb=1|Latvia}}\n! {{vert header|nb=1|Croatia}}\n! {{vert header|nb=1|Portugal}}\n! {{vert header|nb=1|Ireland}}\n! {{vert header|nb=1|Spain}}\n! {{vert header|nb=1|France}}\n! {{vert header|nb=1|Turkey}}\n! {{vert header|nb=1|United Kingdom}}\n! {{vert header|nb=1|Slovenia}}\n! {{vert header|nb=1|Poland}}\n! {{vert header|nb=1|Germany}}\n! {{vert header|nb=1|Estonia}}\n! {{vert header|nb=1|Malta}}\n! {{vert header|nb=1|Greece}}\n! {{vert header|nb=1|Denmark}}\n|-\n|style=\"background:#EFA4A9; height:2px;\"|\n|style=\"background:#EFA4A9;\"|\n|style=\"background:#A4D1EF;\"|\n|style=\"background:#EFA4A9;\"|\n|style=\"background:#EFA4A9;\"|\n|style=\"background:#A4D1EF;\"|\n|style=\"background:#EFA4A9;\"|\n|style=\"background:#EFA4A9;\"|\n|style=\"background:#EFA4A9;\"|\n|style=\"background:#A4EAA9;\"|\n|style=\"background:#EFA4A9;\"|\n|style=\"background:#EFA4A9;\"|\n|style=\"background:#EFA4A9;\"|\n|style=\"background:#EFA4A9;\"|\n|style=\"background:#A4D1EF;\"|\n|style=\"background:#EFA4A9;\"|\n|style=\"background:#EFA4A9;\"|\n|style=\"backgroun