donia}} \u2013 Milanka Ra\u0161ik ([[MTV 2 (Macedonia)|MTV 2]])\n*{{Esc|Romania}} \u2013 [[Andreea Marin]] & [[Leonard Miron]] ([[TVR2]])\n*{{Esc|Switzerland}} \u2013 ''German:'' [[Sandra Studer]] ([[SF zwei|SF2]]), ''French:'' Phil Mundwiller ([[TSR 1]]), ''Italian:'' Jonathan Tedesco ([[RSI La 1|TSI 1]])\n*{{Esc|FR Yugoslavia}}{{ref|b|2}} \u2013 ''Unknown'' (Yu Info)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rtvforum.net/thread-1160-post-143643.html#pid143643 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150929115410/http://www.rtvforum.net/thread-1160-post-143643.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=2015-09-29 |title=Nostalgi\u010dni RTV press clipping |publisher=rtvforum.net |accessdate=2015-09-02}}</ref>\n{{Div col end}}\n\n: 1.{{note|a}} Although Australia was not eligible to enter the contest at the time, the event was broadcast on [[Special Broadcasting Service|SBS]]. As is the case each year, it did not however broadcast it live due to the difference in Australian time zones. This year, the broadcast contained a locally produced addition of a studio audience of young representatives from the competing countries. However, a number of complaints saw the United Kingdom's broadcast, including commentary from [[Terry Wogan]], shown a few weeks later.<ref>[http://www.sbs.com.au/annualreports/sbsannualreport2001.pdf] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070922084530/http://www.sbs.com.au/annualreports/sbsannualreport2001.pdf|date=22 September 2007}}</ref>\n\n: 2.{{note|b}} After the [[breakup of Yugoslavia]], the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia last participated in [[Eurovision Song Contest 1992|1992]]. ''YU Info channel'' broadcast the show, although Yugoslavia did not participate.\n\n==Official album==\n{{Infobox album\n| italic_title = no\n| name         = Eurovision Song Contest: Copenhagen 2001\n| type         = compilation\n| artist       = [[Eurovision Song Contest]]\n| cover        = ESC 2001 album cover.jpg\n| alt          =\n| released     = 5 May 2001\n| recorded     =\n| venue        =\n| studio       =\n| genre        = [[Pop music|Pop]]\n| length       = {{Duration|m=70|s=09}}\n| label        = [[EMI Records|EMI]] / [[CMC International|CMC]]\n| producer     =\n| prev_title   = [[Eurovision Song Contest 2000#Official album|Eurovision Song Contest: Stockholm 2000]]\n| prev_year    = 2000\n| next_title   = [[Eurovision Song Contest 2002#Official album|Eurovision Song Contest: Tallinn 2002]]\n| next_year    = 2002\n}}\n'''''Eurovision Song Contest: Copenhagen 2001''''' was the official compilation album of the 2001 Contest, put together by the European Broadcasting Union and released by [[EMI Records]] and [[CMC International]] on 5 May 2001. The album featured all 23 songs that entered in the 2001 contest.<ref>{{cite web|title=Eurovision Song Contest: Copenhagen 2001|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/release/eurovision-song-contest-copenhagen-2001-mr0002802506/credits|website=allmusic.com|publisher=Allmusic|accessdate=5 November 2014}}</ref>\n{{tracklist\n| headline        = Track listing\n| extra_column    = Artist\n| total_length    = {{Duration|m=70|s=09}}\n| note1 = {{Esccnty|Netherlands}}\n| extra1 = [[Michelle Courtens]]\n| title1 = [[Out on My Own (Michelle song)|Out on My Own]]\n| length1 = 3:21\n| note2 = {{Esccnty|Iceland}}\n| extra2 = [[Two Tricky]]\n| title2 = [[Angel (Two Tricky song)|Angel]]\n| length2 = 3:06\n| note3 = {{Esccnty|Bosnia and Herzegovina}}\n| extra3 = [[Nino Pr\u0161e\u0161]]\n| title3 = [[Hano (song)|Hano]]\n| length3 = 3:00\n| note4 = {{Esccnty|Norway}}\n| extra4 = [[Haldor L\u00e6greid]]\n| title4 = [[On My Own (Haldor L\u00e6greid song)|On My Own]]\n| length4 = 3:04\n| note5 = {{Esccnty|Israel}}\n| extra5 =[[Tal Sondak]]\n| title5 = [[En Davar]]\n| length5 = 3:03\n| note6 =  {{Esccnty|Russia}}\n| extra6 = [[Mumiy Troll]]\n| title6 = [[Lady Alpine Blue]]\n| length6 = 3:00\n| note7 = {{Esccnty|Sweden}}\n| extra7 = [[Friends (group)|Friends]]\n| title7 = [[Listen To Your Heartbeat]]\n| lengt